metadata.name: Mosaic #835
metadata.description:
---
Notes:
- Click to pause/unpause
- The aspect ratio is fixed 1:1 because of the way the grid and movements are generated to make sure they're the same on all screens. 
---
Description:
An 80X80 grid of tiles are scrambled, shuffled, shifted, streamed, transported,
conveyed, moved, deposited. 

There are 15 initial tile states and 5 color palettes. A set of 12 unique motion patterns
are generated for each piece. 
---
Acknowledgements:
This piece is inspired by Kim Asendorf, whose pixel-level algorithms I'm
transfixed by, and Ksawery Komputery, whose algorithmic tile-works I'm crazy
about. 
---
Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5.js 
December 2021, Germany

metadata.name: estruturas.14 #40
metadata.description:
"estruturas.14" is my first project using the p5js library for generative art.

The aesthetic concept that I attempted to translate onto the canvas was the formation of interconnected points that form structures. fxrand is used to set the position, dot/dash size, movement pattern, and canvas position at random. This randomization is also reflected in the color palettes used.

The vibrating movement and the structure's movement were designed to give the impression of something alive. It's like a mechanism. We are connected to the structure by a combination of interactive movement, point connections, and vibration.

Composition

- 22 pallets, each with 5 colors

- Background color: white or black

- fxrand determines the grayscale using square or ellipse orbs.

- 5 - 20 "estruturas"

Interactivity

- To coordinate the movement of the "estruturas," press and drag the mouse left button; 

- To coordinate movement and orb size, press and drag the scroll button.

- To return "estruturas" to its original position, press T; to stop the return movement, press P.

- To save a png file, press S.

This code is licenced with CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

Special thanks to everyone who assisted me in getting in touch with this new library and, as a result, with a new set of possibilities.

metadata.name: Daedalian Pyramids #84
metadata.description: This generative piece is about taking sides. There are elements on the scene, and yet it is hard to see whether there is an inside or an outside to be found. What contains, and what is contained? What is fixed, and what is broken? Who are we, dwellers of this matrix with so much structure and so little essence?

metadata.description: Ghozt! Guardian of the Death and Watchers of Sinners, is an ancient legend who has been guarding the dead for thousands of years. He is always on the lookout for sinners and will come down and punish them in a very scary manner. May Ghozt be your guardian so that you can peacefully die.
